  </Info>
  <Properties>
    <contentGrid>
      <Value><![CDATA[{
  "contentData": [
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "f170b29c-338f-4ab8-a5c4-f72c90826f69",
      "key": "a8deb37f-905d-4275-ac2d-d58cbb7ec07e",
      "udi": null,
      "values": []
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "c345e5ce-768f-47e0-968a-e7859dbe0b07",
      "key": "6f7eb12c-f6d2-444e-88e8-10214791df9e",
      "udi": null,
      "values": []
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "6d9468f1-b715-419b-9b2e-5221a4bab789",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "What It Does"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Automatically lists all titled feature blocks in the same area"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EThe Table of Contents feature automatically scans the block grid area it is placed in and generates a navigation list from all sibling feature blocks that have a Feature Title set. It requires no configuration \u2014 simply add it to an area and it builds the table of contents from the blocks around it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike the In-Page Navigation feature which uses an editor-driven picker, the Table of Contents is entirely automatic. It discovers its siblings at render time and lists them in the order they appear in the area.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "This feature uses the featureComponentNoConfiguration composition \u2014 no editable properties, everything is auto-generated."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "4df24e2a-2cb9-4025-a9e6-3717944c03ab",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Area-Aware Navigation"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Only lists blocks from its own area, not the entire page"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EA key design decision is that the Table of Contents only lists feature blocks within the same area where it is placed. In a three-column layout like layout363, a TOC in the middle area will only show blocks from the middle area \u2014 it won\u0027t include blocks from the left or right sidebars.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is achieved by the view scanning the block grid layout structure to find which area contains the TOC block, then iterating through the sibling blocks in that same area. This means you could have multiple TOCs on a page, each scoped to its own area.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "078605bf-658a-45e1-a25d-639b280ff5eb",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Responsive Collapse"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Expands on desktop, collapses behind a toggler on smaller screens"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EOn desktop screens at the large breakpoint and above, the Table of Contents displays as an expanded card showing all the section links. On smaller screens, the list collapses behind a toggler button, saving vertical space while still giving users quick access to the navigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen a visitor taps a link on mobile, the list automatically collapses after navigating to the section. This uses Bootstrap\u0027s Collapse component with the same card and list-group pattern used throughout UmBootstrap.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "31b55005-ddac-4b61-adce-a413af06b5df",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "How It Differs from In-Page Navigation"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Two complementary features with different approaches"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EUmBootstrap provides three navigation features that work at different levels. The Nested Descendants feature navigates between pages in a section. The In-Page Navigation feature sits in a sidebar and lets editors pick specific blocks to link to. The Table of Contents sits inline with the content and auto-generates from titled blocks in its area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe In-Page Navigation is editor-driven: the content editor uses a Contentment picker to choose which blocks appear and in what order. The Table of Contents is automatic: it discovers everything for itself. This makes it ideal for pages where you want a quick overview without any editorial effort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe In-Page Navigation also provides a sticky sidebar on desktop and an offcanvas bottom bar on mobile. The Table of Contents stays inline with the content flow, collapsing on smaller screens.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "c0878d1c-1cfc-4ad0-99fe-eea94153311b",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Where to Place It"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Best suited to the main content area of any layout"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EThe Table of Contents is designed for the main content area \u2014 the middle column in a multi-column layout, or the full width in a single-column layout. It sits at the top of the content, giving readers an overview of what follows before they start scrolling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBecause it auto-generates from blocks in its own area, placing it in a sidebar would only list the sidebar content, which is rarely useful. For sidebar navigation, use the In-Page Navigation or Nested Descendants features instead.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe feature works with any layout that accepts feature blocks. Simply add it as the first block in an area and it will list all the titled siblings that follow it.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "d5bfea49-0733-48ff-9ee0-d83c01a4cbf4",
      "key": "3db9c743-aec2-46ae-9a37-81bd257bd6a9",
      "udi": null,
      "values": [
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureTitle",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Technical Notes"
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureDescription",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "Implementation details for developers"
        },
        {
          "alias": "richTextContent",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": {
            "blocks": {
              "contentData": [],
              "settingsData": [],
              "expose": [],
              "Layout": {}
            },
            "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EThe Table of Contents view traverses the block grid layout structure to find the area containing the TOC block by matching its own \u003Ccode\u003EContentKey\u003C/code\u003E. It then iterates the sibling blocks in that area, filtering for feature blocks with a \u003Ccode\u003EfeaturePropertyFeatureTitle\u003C/code\u003E value.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFragment IDs use the same \u003Ccode\u003ESlugHelper.ToSlug()\u003C/code\u003E method as all other features \u2014 a slugified title with a 4-character GUID suffix for collision resistance. ScrollSpy highlights the active section as the user scrolls.\u003C/p\u003E"
          }
        },
        {
          "alias": "featurePropertyFeatureSummary",
          "culture": null,
          "editorAlias": null,
          "segment": null,
          "value": "The view file is featureTableOfContents.cshtml in the blockgrid Components folder."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
